post.author: bpanjavan
post.title: Programming too much?
post.content:
This post is about how my developer lifestyle seems to have made its way into other things.  Last week I accompanied my father in law who specializes in wood flooring.  I lent him a hand because I know how tough the labor can be, but a well known secret is that I was really eager to learn something new, especially something that requires skill and craftsmanship.  I doubt that's a unique characteristic for a developer.

I started out just carrying supplies, but I was quickly eager to try the more difficult task of laying down the wood.  Make no mistake.  This requires precision, AND strength.  I was being very careful, especially my first 20 pieces.  I was taking it really slow, making sure there was not a millimeter of space in between pieces, and hitting with the mallet at an near perfect 45 degree angle.  My father in law noticed this with amusement.  Everyone appreciates when you try to do a good job, but it was apparent that at the rate I was going, I would NEVER finish.

He watched me lay down the next few pieces, and when I still thought they needed more precision, he would tell me "That's good enough, move on!”  The remaining time I made adjustments, sacrificing my precision a little but speeding up my pace a lot.  I was worried about how the floor would look when the product was finished.  But…

You wouldn't be surprised to know that the floor turned out perfectly.  More specifically, perfectly aligned.  It seemed that my extra care and caution really wasn't making much difference after all, though I'm sure it made a little difference.  The owners stopped by for spot checking and what do you know, they thought it was perfect too.  And clearly they were detail oriented people because they were fussing about little spots and cracks in other parts of the house.

If it's not becoming obvious how this ties into programming, you're a slow thinker, or I'm just bad at implication.  There's a diminishing ROI to trying to achieve 100% bug-free code.  When software gets good enough, the client won't care about you spending an extra 80 hours of billing time fixing little details.  Heck, they may not even notice!  My father in law is not a cynical person, and neither should you be.  Just don't forget to be practical.
